When customizing OpenStack Horizon design, multiple files have to be changed
because properties are hard-coded into different files.For instance, the red
color into '_accordion_nav.scss' is defined multiple times into this file. Some
Sass files use -webkit prefix on CSS3 properties while other prefixes are not

to read.

This commit facilitates the customization of OpenStack Horizon. By defining all
color values with variables, edition of multiples files is avoided. Also,
prefixes are now defined into mixins definition to manage all existing prefixes:
opera, IE, webkit, old firefox. Finally, '_charts.scss' now respects the same
syntax that the other files.

Change-Id: Ieb3a116dca7bca947b493666eca12600354adbe3

commit_message:
Normalize and parameterize sass files to simplify design changes

When customizing OpenStack Horizon design, multiple files have to be changed
because properties are hard-coded into different files.For instance, the red
color into '_accordion_nav.scss' is defined multiple times into this file. Some
Sass files use -webkit prefix on CSS3 properties while other prefixes are not
managed. It implies that minor and old browsers don't have the same design.
'_charts.scss' file doesn't respect the same syntax that others and is harder
to read.

This commit facilitates the customization of OpenStack Horizon. By defining all
color values with variables, edition of multiples files is avoided. Also,
prefixes are now defined into mixins definition to manage all existing prefixes:
opera, IE, webkit, old firefox. Finally, '_charts.scss' now respects the same
syntax that the other files.

Change-Id: Ieb3a116dca7bca947b493666eca12600354adbe3

commit_message:
Sample developer sandbox dashboard for UI development

This example adds a new Horizon dashboard used to experiment with
Horizon components in a live installation. This allows a developer
to experiment with new components without editing any of the
production Horizon dashboards.  This example also includes a single
panel with a simple Angular based wait spinner control, built on the
default Horizon wait spinner.

This patch is intended as a developer sample, not for release.

Change-Id: If8a06a3031cffec76d087d2cb2dfce12e70da8bf

[{'number': 4, 'created': '2014-11-20 17:43:26.000000000', 'files': ['horizon/templates/horizon/common/_workflow_step_update_members.html'], 'message': 'Fixes list stacking behavior in users/available project screen

When a user opens the members tab for a project (Identity->
Projects->Edit Project->Project Members), and then shrinks
the browser to a narrow width, the list of available and current
project members merge into one list, while the two headings
become stacked on top of each other, rather than being
separated by their respective lists. The root cause of this
behavior was the arrangement of divs, which had both headers
in a single div, followed by both lists in distinct divs

and lists side by side, the browser would do that, but if the
space was shrunken the dom elements are rendered top to bottom.
To fix this, I re-arranged the divs containing the elements
to be a left header plus list, and a right header plus list.

commit_message:
Fixes list stacking behavior in users/available project screen

When a user opens the members tab for a project (Identity->
Projects->Edit Project->Project Members), and then shrinks
the browser to a narrow width, the list of available and current
project members merge into one list, while the two headings
become stacked on top of each other, rather than being
separated by their respective lists. The root cause of this
behavior was the arrangement of divs, which had both headers
in a single div, followed by both lists in distinct divs
afterwards. When there is enough space to put the headers
and lists side by side, the browser would do that, but if the
space was shrunken the dom elements are rendered top to bottom.
To fix this, I re-arranged the divs containing the elements
to be a left header plus list, and a right header plus list.

Change-Id: Ibd3d6178e8a960d54ac147594efcdabbdfedd861
Closes-bug:1346647

commit_message:
Fixing files used as panel template by startdash

run_tests.sh options 'startdash' and 'startpanel' are used to
automatically generate a new dashboard, or new panel in horizon.

The fix for bug #1325099 introduced a regression where panels added to a
newly created dashboard would not display their main content area. Also
the automatically generated panel Django template was inconsistent with the
tutorial documentation.

Investigation revealed that #1325099 changed the default panel Django template
file to include the horizon 'base.html', instead of the base.html file
from the parent dashboard. This is consistent with existing dashboards,
but inconsistent with the sample dashboard and panel files used by
startdash and startpanel

A more complete fix is:
1) Remove the sample dashboard Django template file. No other
dashboards have Django template files. Other existing dashboards place
all content in panels registered with that dashboard
2) Fix the sample panel Django template file to no longer reference the
parent dashboard's base.html
3) Update the documentation to be consistent with the new panel's Django
template files

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1401332

Change-Id: I87e67cb647a10494ca1558a0f3ce7179d582a38e

commit_message:
Directive to allow editing of table cell values

A widget to support Launch Instance workflow. When used,
this directive allows a value to be editable when clicked, and shows
the user a select menu listing options that are pre-defined from the
controller. When the value changes it is passed back to the parent
ngModel.

Mockup: http://invis.io/8F2185WPR

Partially Implements: blueprint launch-instance-redesign

Change-Id: Idef5bd696d26ee8708f3104b7a7ee581bf195395

commit_message:
Modal Wait Spinner Demo

Adds a UI "sandbox" dashboard into Horizon in order to experiment with
the Angular-based modal wait spinner component, compare it to the
existing Horizon wait spinner, and see how the new component can
be used from other modal components like the wizard.

Change-Id: I541a2d665dfa40824be43a780a5d30a8e1a6eeb5

commit_message:
Configurable instance detail tab group

Improve usability when some tabs cannot be used in specific
environments by hiding. For example, VMware environment
doesn't support the console log feature. In that case,
usability will improve if the console log tab is hidden.

commit_message:
Add DATABASES to settings.py

Horizon needs more space to handle session data. With the Identity
API moving towards V3 (that has a significantly enlarged token),
we need to work with sessions beyond 4KB.
Between the types of session backend offered by Django, we decided
to opt by the cached_db option. In order to do that and avoid
problems with devstack, we need to follow a procedure:
1 - Add the DATABASES setting on the settings.py to allow 'syncdb'
2 - Make devstack do a 'syncdb' to create the base on deploying
3 - Finally, set the backend to 'cached_db'

Change-Id: I07904dddf75ab4213d9fe4f637f83354feffc1d7
Partial-bug: 1382079

commit_message:
Display profile information in network details

When the Cisco N1K neutron plugin is being used, network
create requires a network profile to be used. When a network
is subsequently created, this fix will now display the profile
information - id and name, in the network details page.
Involves changes to the views.py file in order to obtain the
profile name and corresponding updates to the test file.

Closes-bug: #1260438

Change-Id: I1af1598446e437c8cb5234e9a218541e87cbce2d

commit_message:
Fix display of ports when associating floating IP

No port was visible, making it impossible to associate a floating IP to
a port of an instance. This happens when the gateway router is not in
the same tenant as the instance, but still attached to a network shared
accross tenants -- because we were only considering ports in our tenant
to find gateway routers that are reachable.

This fixes a regression introduced in commit 277c7bc7.

Co-Authored-By: Thomas Bechtold <tbechtold@suse.com>
Change-Id: I99c136789382775deb72a253ee6f8339f08bae01
Related-Bug: #1252403
Closes-Bug: #1394051

commit_message:
Ignore Exception in process of Edit Attachments

In the process of "Edit attachments", if we try to detach the
associated VM instance which is already died (by whatever reason)
then Horizon dashboard always pop up the error of
"Error: Unable to retrieve volume information" and the purpose of detaching
can not be completed.

This patch is to ignore this kind of Exception so that the process
can be continued.

Closes-Bug: #1405530
Change-Id: I525973facd02dc98deccb6b22b07208bcc188e7d

Add "Back To Previous Page" link from all Detail pages

This will give users a quick step back to the full Instances table

Volume snapshots should only show snapshots which are
linked to bootable volumes. This is not available via
a direct API filter. You have to check if the volume
snapshots parent volume is bootable.

This fix does incur extra performance overhead because
of this.  The alternative is to just list all

Closes-Bug: #1434662
'}]
commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Only show bootable vol snaps

Volume snapshots should only show snapshots which are
linked to bootable volumes. This is not available via
a direct API filter. You have to check if the volume
snapshots parent volume is bootable.

This fix does incur extra performance overhead because
of this.  The alternative is to just list all
volume snapshots and let users guess which ones are actually
bootable.

Change-Id: Icbdaaa93c95a3a63adf4a655ffbd608e7ce39769
Closes-Bug: #1434662

commit_message:
Primary Project made optional in horizon

While creating a user, the primary project field
was mandatory in Horizon and was optional in
python-keystoneclient. Now, the primary project
has been made optional in Horizon as well
and will allow user to create a user without
mapping it to any project.

The command keystone user-create is now
consistent on both the interfaces.

Changes as per the comments received:
1. Added new test cases
2. To maintain consistency between CreateUserForm
and UpdateUserform, Primary Project has been
made optional in the UpdateUserForm as well.

Change-Id: I94545e70b6fc364d8e92e5c05de304f41500282d
Closes-Bug: #1285138

commit_message:

basic instances from the first step of the Angular-based

commit_message:
Using a one 'statistics_list' for all resources

Currently, in 'metering' dashboard we use a 'statistics_list' request
for every resource which we want to look. It bulks a ceilometer-api
aspecially at huge amount of samples. Otherwise, we can use one statistics
request and split result in CeilometerUsage, because statistics_list supports
a groupby parameter.

Change-Id: I4f8436223fd3f3a786a2a42a219f892a4fc69bbe

created by admin during the test case setup.

executed against a single devstack instance
concurrently

commit_message:
Use Cinder limit API for used quota

As we currently calculate Cinder quota manually in Horizon there's no
way to account for the Cinder setting that specifies whether to include
snapshot storage in the used gigabytes count for quota calculation.

This change removes the manual calculation of Cinder quotas and uses the
response from the Cinder limits API, which has been around since Icehouse.

See Cinder commits:
  - 8aa8ebc0a0d0f459e9293f9ff5a5f8358fd01b9a and
  - c9c6befe7e19adc168aefe1cfaeac8d68dd398fa

Closes-Bug: #1283281
Co-Authored-By: Vahid Hashemian <vahidhashemian@us.ibm.com>
Change-Id: I4dc14b7d08d58db2a00124f44e80ebdb329d4a82

commit_message:
Adds auto fade-out for AJAX messages (a new setting)

Before, auto fade-out was enabled only for non-AJAX messages,
because fade-out function was subscribed only on "DOM ready" event
(with jQuery .ready(...) method). It fires only after initial DOM
load and it is not working when DOM is modified later.

This patch subscribes fade-out function to an event that corresponds
to moment when AJAX message is shown if the `auto_fade_alerts.mode` is
set to 'ajax' or 'both' (a new setting).

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1442288
Co-Authored-By: Timur Sufiev <tsufiev@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I03be3bed878102702651dfa36007f83974d1b8fd

commit_message:
Fix popover positions in network topology

Router popovers are now positioned correctly next to
router representation in Firefox and IE. If popover
overflows window to the right and enough room is on
the left, display balloon to the left of device.

Change-Id: I10ae9ace84605adde3be760aae0418266d3c261d
Closes-Bug: #1403216

commit_message:
Feature Toggles

Work in Progress...

A patch that allows for features to be toggled on and off based on local_settings.py.

A feature that is off can (presumably) be committed while in prototype state, allowing
for easier incremental development. A feature should not be enabled by default (toggle
removed) until the feature is production ready.

Change-Id: I3fcf426a4f09bed304982d6969af050f7f15c096

commit_message:
WIP Angular Users Panel - Admin Password check

This is a settings-dependent feature.

To test it out, add the following to local_settings.py:
REST_API_REQUIRED_SETTINGS = ['ENFORCE_PASSWORD_CHECK']
Restart server.

Then when you click on "Change Password", you should see
an additional required field that will ask for the
logged-in admin's password.

Change-Id: Icec097eb40958c3aba5dbc36ede40b83fab8749d

commit_message:
Add Volume Backend Name to Create Volume Type

This patch combines the steps to set up volume backend name for a
volume type into the volume type creation process by adding the new
"Volume Backend Name" choice field to the Create Volume Type dialog.

Change-Id: I1547adacb2c8f50196e9e7c6f93222a428a0b024
Implements: blueprint volume-type-set-backend-name

IE9 has limit on the number of css rules can be parsed in a single css file.

commit_message:
fix bug - IE9 cuts off css rules

bug link: https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1417314

IE9 has limit on the number of css rules can be parsed in a single css file.
The limit is 4095 = (4k - 1). This causes the new css rules for angular-
based widget styled improperly.

This change moves the new css code for angular-based widgets
to another css file and keep the remaining page styling untouched.

Link:
http://blogs.msdn.com/b/ieinternals/archive/2011/05/14/10164546.aspx

Change-Id: I9e689cb23835e6b1354e6c05506de5fbb4ed965c

commit_message:
Adding new util: next unique ID

There are some places we want to use ID in the UI. A hard-coded value
cannot be guaranteed to be unique.  This change provides a utility
function to get the next unique ID.

Applied to Launch Instance wizard form fields.

Change-Id: I35bb7c3225ba811526955816ad6655e3aaae9ed6
Closes-Bug: #1453260

commit_message:
Port and Port-Range fields' asterisk missing in Access-Security tab

The 'Port', 'From Port' and 'To Port' are the required fields for
managing rules in Access and Security tab, but do not have the
asterisk marked against them. To replicate this, please follow
Projects -> Access and Security -> Add/Edit Rules (on any security
group that has been created).

Change-Id: Ic18963a75040c99d9fc5b30a487368fbde305225
Closes-Bug: 1292165

commit_message:
LoadBalancers' Add Member form has missing asterisk for 'Members' list

Under Load Balancers section, while adding a new Member to the pool,
if the 'Member Source' is selected as 'Active instances', a 'Members'
multiple-select field comes up. Here atleast 1 member must be
selected to submit the form. Hence, this field should be marked with
an asterisk.

Closes-Bug: #1396983
Closes-Bug: #1392182
Change-Id: Iba818ad5e32e635faa568edfe2c69c12cfe0bc5b

commit_message:
WIP re-design of top-level Horizon menu

Reverted project context selection so that it would work. Styling is
still a mess due to ul li style bleed through.

Fixed menu content for project, identity and admin

Latest update:

- masthead
- activate some links for demo
- move tab labels up
- project dropdown fixed
- masthead style tweaks
- menu items now stacked for smaller widths
- tweaks to menu style
- added region picker
- needs to be context-aware (admin vs. user, actual menu items enabled)
- many little style tweaks

Change-Id: I05aa2b03d21377a2998c7c4da8ba043a823c62e7

Updated error message when image creation fails

Initially if image creation fails, the message that is displayed
provides insufficient details for the exception. With this fix,
more clear error message will be displayed to the user.

Closes-Bug: #1261755

commit_message:
Co-locate common test infrastructure

This patch provides a "test-framework" directory and
a "spec_framework" array in jasmine_tests.py to collect
test code needed by multiple different jasmine test files.

Similar to angular-mocks.js, when test code depends on some
common test-only code, it is nice to have that in one place
and included separately (and before) any of the spec files
get included.

Change-Id: Ie614e492eb5036e21f06bf8458fb3f6f6af0657c

commit_message:
Refactor project instance test

Refactoring the test_launch_instance_post test as suggested in
review for bug 1260436. There are four distinct other users of
test_launch_instance_post apart from the test itself.

commit_message:
JSCS - Demo patch for error filter

This file demonstrates adding several kinds of line too long
errors, and proves that they are ignored by jscs.

They also add some examples of lines that are STILL errors
because they aren't an exact match for the filter

To test:
jscs horizon/static/framework/jscs_error_tests.spec.js
jscs horizon/static/framework/jscs_error_tests.js

To see the errors again, change jscs_error_filter.js to return
immediately

Change-Id: Ib5f515b8995b51d960f70c5116a4198b7604c552

commit_message:
Integration tests - Object store

Implemented page for testing basic operations with containers.
Scenario:
  * create new container
  * check if is present in the list
  * remove the container

Object store service shoudn't be installed by default, so there was also
added option to horizon.conf for enable/disable these subset of tests.

Partially implements blueprint: integration-tests-object-store
Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I6ad1267c10d32f14a29f245d00d95da95d353dc7

commit_message:
WIP: Converting horizon JS to use use i18n library

This is the first in a series of dependent patches that
wean Angular away from global gettext references in favor
of an injectable service.

This first patch removes the use of gettext references in
constants (which can't take advantage of an injected
'gettext' service.

TODO: Check for other constants that use gettext
TODO: Test that strings still appear correctly in UI
TODO: Create next dependent patch that uses injected gettext
      in normal code.

Co-Authored-By: Tyr Johanson <tyr@hp.com>
Change-Id: I3a76b90e1c3e889387597e8a296d8efb0f2e2367
Partial-Bug: 1446739

commit_message:
fixed row update of firewall table

In firewall table, after creating a
firewall the row should be updated
whenever the status of the firewall
changes. but it is not and it get
struck in the pending_create status.

It needs page reload to update the row.

In this patch, the added Update row class
will reload a row after the status change.

Change-Id: I1558722618cdeed016ae28c773a36c4a928b3a23
closes-Bug: #1424571

commit_message:
make_xstatic_setup_cfg.py initial commit

Our xstatic repos aren't auto-uploading to pypi as they should be
because their build process isn't matching the old standard way.

Now, pbr requires a more boiler-plate setup.py and a not-boiler-plate
setup.cfg file.  This setup.cfg file will need to be re-made each and
every time any of the xstatic packages are updated.  Thus, I've made a
tool to remake that setup.cfg file whenever necessary.

An example of the setup.cfg file being added can be found here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/204283/

Change-Id: I1950bd366f9a531ec2916a0942cbc32d683d8072

subject: Make tests pass with random PYTHONHASHSEED
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 5623, 'name': 'David Lyle', 'email': 'dklyle0@gmail.com', 'username': 'david-lyle'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2015-06-16 23:55:38.000000000', 'files': ['horizon/test/tests/tables.py', 'openstack_dashboard/test/api_tests/nova_rest_tests.py', 'openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/overview/tests.py', 'openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/instances/tests.py', 'openstack_dashboard/test/api_tests/glance_rest_tests.py', 'openstack_dashboard/test/api_tests/keystone_rest_tests.py', 'tox.ini', 'openstack_dashboard/dashboards/identity/projects/workflows.py'], 'message': 'Make tests pass with random PYTHONHASHSEED

Some of the API tests relied on specific order of keys used in
serialization. This order would change, if PYTHONHASHSEED changed,
therefore the tests would fail.

This change improves this situation, by comparing json/html and not
relying on their string representation, where relevant.

Also makes order of calls to in _update_project_members predictable, by
sorting the keys of a defaultdict, returned by api.keystone.get_project_users_roles

Finally this change ignores some of the checks for django 1.4, that may
fail due to an incorrect behaviour of django test.html parser

The change removes PYTHONHASHSEED=0 requirement from tox.ini

Closes-Bug: #1348818
Change-Id: I09c6be62f7bfc5709ea48c55e5412cf0850e8fc8
'}]
commit_message:
Make tests pass with random PYTHONHASHSEED

Some of the API tests relied on specific order of keys used in
serialization. This order would change, if PYTHONHASHSEED changed,
therefore the tests would fail.

This change improves this situation, by comparing json/html and not
relying on their string representation, where relevant.

Also makes order of calls to in _update_project_members predictable, by
sorting the keys of a defaultdict, returned by api.keystone.get_project_users_roles

Finally this change ignores some of the checks for django 1.4, that may
fail due to an incorrect behaviour of django test.html parser

The change removes PYTHONHASHSEED=0 requirement from tox.ini

Closes-Bug: #1348818
Change-Id: I09c6be62f7bfc5709ea48c55e5412cf0850e8fc8

commit_message:
LBaas v1 Associate Monitor to Pool Fails

The associate monitor fails to show monitors to choose from
within horizon.  The monitor list code has changed where
you can no longer list monitors with a filter criteria.
This change switches to grab needed monitors one at a time.

Closes-bug: #1398754
(cherry picked from commit 0dde489a81ea8599e75d45ac0be34048a5c366d0)

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/api/lbaas.py

commit_message:
Removing Network Profile support in stable/kilo

Network profile is not supported in stable/kilo by the Cisco N1KV
ML2 driver. As the patch for enabling/disabling network profile
support based on a configurable parameter was rejected, this patch
pulls out the network profile code completly from stable/kilo.

This patch is necessary for horizon to be functional with Cisco
N1KV ML2 driver.

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/api/neutron.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/router/nexus1000v/tests.py

Change-Id: I1ef2f489c9bb2adfbe3174c3667539c59562966f
Closes-bug: #1475190
(cherry picked from commit d29a68c4f3fa81fa8b3aa19e0de71b69ba9cb015)

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Show Admin Password

We need to show admin password if enabled for the hypervisor type.

Note: To test, you need to add the following to local_settings.py
REST_API_REQUIRED_SETTINGS = ['OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURES']
OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURES = {
    'can_set_password': True
}

Change can_set_password to False to see it not show up.

Must restart the server.

Change-Id: Id17c54c92c9d160c9a3df2b153134d348c13dff5
Closes-Bug: #1439905
Co-Authored-By: Travis Tripp <travis.tripp@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Brian Tully  <brian.tully@hp.com>

commit_message:
Demo for transfer tables

There are two sets of transfer tables on the same page.

One showing the ability to allocate only one item. If an
item from the available table is selected, the allocated
item will be swapped out with the new item. The other one
shows transfer tables with re-ordering and multi allocation.
Drag and drop to re-order the allocated table. Filtering and
sort are enabled on the available table.

Demo only. This patch will NOT be merged.

To test:
http://localhost:9000/identity/users/transfer/

Change-Id: Id514fbcb9f1baf26e9daca55ae490306bff77e25

Demo for editable table field directive

Currently showing the ability to select a different flavor, security
group and keypair. When any of the editable fields are clicked, a
select menu appears with the available options (defined in the
controller). When the value is changed, it gets updated in the parent
ngModel

Demo only. This patch will NOT be merged.

Mockup: http://invis.io/8F2185WPR

To test:
Click on the "Editable Demo" link within the UI Sandbox/Angular Widgets
dashboard panel
e.g., http://127.0.0.1:8000/ui_sandbox/

commit_message:
Clientside table rendering

This patch introduces a mixin for table-views that would provide a JSON
endpoint. This is done to preserve existing functionality, and would
shift the bulk of rendering to Javascript in subsequent patches.

To take advantage of this feature, follow 2 steps:
1. Inherit JSONTableMixin in your view class and specify an encoder_class.
2. View the JSON endpoint: /{mytableviewurl}?format=json

Co-Authored-By: Thai Tran <tqtran@us.ibm.com>
Implements: blueprint table-client-rendering
Change-Id: I55469bcd9158873709de1d19ff2021206737782e

commit_message:
Enhance Dashboard for Cisco FWaaS

Enhance Network/Firewalls/Firewalls to support additional
attributes (neutron router interface and firewall direction)
which are required by Cisco FWaaS.

"+Create Firewall", "Edit Firewall", and "Firewall Details"
will be enhanced accordingly.

Change-Id: I7fb114ebdda60a94373447b5a29ee1ef20b145bc
Implements: blueprint bp-cisco-fwaas-horizon

commit_message:
Demo for Re-designed Tables

This patch is a demo of the re-designed tables. The table
shows the identity users table. Filtering and check-all are
enabled, but action buttons are dummies only. Reduce the
browser width to see responsiveness in action (lower priority
columns become hidden). Table is sortable (default is email
in reverse order).

To view, browse to:
http://localhost:9000/identity/users/list/

This patch will NOT be merged.

Implemention of patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/147393

Change-Id: I89e577453f64da6ad000ab51508d1c55c45da7d4

commit_message:
Add Magic Search to users table

Identity api V3 supports user api filter, V2 does not.  Added
support to detect active identity api version, and user's table
keys off that whether to do client side or api side faceted
filtering.

Depends on following patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/166374/2

Co-Authored-By: David Kavanagh <david.kavanagh@eucalyptus.com>
Co-Authored-By: Aaron Sahlin <asahlin@us.ibm.com>

Partially Implemenents: blueprint filtered-client-side-table

Change-Id: If8a83e76a7a749f0d79400a3db4446e694616131

commit_message:
Updated network name parameter as optional

Previously, while creating a port, network name was mandatory
and was in read only mode. So if a network without name is used
to create port, the port creation fails. This issue has been
resolved by making the network name field as optional.

Added unit test case for the same.

Change-Id: I174e7bf531a93937df5d325711e5160a65409099
Closes-Bug: #1426252

commit_message:
Add support for Docker image format

The 'Docker' format is added to the default list of supported
formats so it can be selected from the list of formats when creating
or updating an image. When the docker format is selected, the
disk_format and container_format properties are set appropriately.
This also includes changes to the Format column and filter for the
Images table to handle this type.

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/images/images/forms.py

Closes-Bug: #1455179
Change-Id: Ie705c86d47c0b6035373b9311454748122185988
(cherry picked from commit 12550cb9b9abbd3d7c3e078c5e1e55d7804a733e)

commit_message:
Add Windows SMB share driver

This patch proposes a new share driver, handling Windows service
instances and exporting SMB shares.

WinRM is used for managing the service instances, allowing
password or certificate based authentication.

A new service instance manager is introduced, handling Windows
instances. One requirement is that Cloudbase-Init is present on the
instance.

If AD credentials are provided via security services, the instance
is joined to an AD domain. This can be leveraged in order to set
user based permissions.

A CI testing this driver will be up by L-3. Meanwhile, a link to
Tempest results can be found on the blueprint page whiteboard.

Change-Id: Ice5ee63ee4dc2cfcb41567214c165c2705421920
Implements: blueprint windows-smb-support

commit_message:
rename the opt scheduler_default_filters

The value of "scheduler_default_filters" is what filters are used
by users really and it is not the default one, which makes users
misleading.

commit_message:
Pass X-Auth-Token into download snapshot request

Since 7.0 the diagnostic snapshow aren't shared by Nginx anymore, and
any request to download goes through Nailgun and therefore requires
authentication token.

Closes-Bug: #1492207

Change-Id: I29e1a5142dd7c7050ba58b68f1161eba339cf53f
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Comment out dl.fedoraproject.org mirror

We are seeing lots of CI failures with 404's in them
today. This comments out the dl.fedoraproject.org
mirror in an attempt to find a mirror that isn't broken.

Related-bug: #1492022

Change-Id: Ic0c63a7b1c525189656272872eaf80d8114d66e2

commit_message:
filter_class_names is never passed

Currently,we always use the filters from CONF.scheduler_default_filters.
the filter_class_names parameter in method get_filtered_hosts from class
HostManager is never used. We can removed this parameter safely.

Change-Id: I089fca7e6fa07e4c6e84c39ee9a6e371c763d839
Closes-Bug:#1403020

commit_message:
Support Instances->Disassociate IP action for Neutron setups

When using Neutron-powered networking (vs. Nova-Networks) an instance
can have more than one floating IP assigned to it, but since Horizon
retrieves list of instance's IPs from Nova which doesn't distinguish
between private and floating IPs, it's hard to offer user a choice
which floating IP to disassociate in Instances table.

A different approach is chosen: when the user presses 'Disassociate
IP' button, he is redirected to Access&Security->Floating IPs tab,
where he sees only floating IPs that are linked to the instance which
IP he's disassociating. To make this happen, a hidden FilterAction is
added to Floating IPs table, and the redirect link contains filter
query which is applied once we at Floating IPs table.

Change-Id: Ib91ded75966fc34bf698f77a61299e962bdd6a0b
Closes-Bug: #1226003

commit_message:
Prevent unintentional detaching volume from instance

There is a case that unintentional volume is detached from instance
in terminate instance API.
Because in _shutdown_instance(), all volume block device mapping is
collected and detached by the condition of volume id.
So, if instance has redundant volume block device mapping which made
by attaching failure, terminate instance API detach another volume.
This patch checks consistency of detaching volume and instance
between nova and cinder.

Also this patch moves get_volume_connector() call out of loop
to avoid unnecessary multiple calls.

Co-Authored-By: Haruka Tanizawa <h-tanizawa@intellilink.co.jp>
Change-Id: Ic71c735bf5a6792966ae321c3545f6ad46e932ed
Closes-Bug: #1377161

commit_message:
Move out loading horizon modals to a named function

So it could be called not only on clicking some links, but on the
other events as well, e.g. drag-and-drop.

This change is not currently used by any other horizon/
openstack_dashboard code, it's used only by the murano-dashboard
plugin. So please feel to ignore it :).

Change-Id: Ic17eefb142326c02309b8758166bb9f3c0219164

commit_message:
Pipeline was erroneously overwritten

The pipeline yaml was overwritten with the default value. This
fix it and enable the publishers to send to Monasca.

Also when installing from within VPN the get_url in Ansible
tend to timeout, the script adds a very long timeout to eliminate
the problem.

Also there is now a check to see if the role to be removed from the
monasca-vagrant was alredy removed, in that case it will not try
again. This makes the ceilosca.sh runneable several times without
the need of removing the monasca-vagrant folder. Docs updated.

Change-Id: If09cfc2e1c1a485b1794372f272f86b47ef52079

commit_message:
Add ability to update provider_id during init

During the Liberty release we added the ability to store
a provider_id for a volume in the Cinder database.  This
simplifies a number of things for back ends when accessing
volumes.

One missing piece here however is that we have no way to
populate this data for existing deployments if/when they
upgrade.

This patch provides a simple solution that issues an update
call to the drivers on host init.  It works by fetching a
list of volumes for the specific host, and passes those in
to the driver.  The driver can do nothing, or it can go
through and sync up the Cinder ID's with it's internal
ID's and return the provider update info.

Change-Id: Ib3b078a6f492afada24e534f380f5f014033d603

commit_message:
VMs fail to start when force_config_drive=Always

When force_config_drive=Always is set, VMs that did not previously
have a config drive created for them will fail to start.

Steps to recreate:
1. Spawn an instance without a config drive
2. Change force_config_drive=True
3. Restart nova-compute
4. Stop the instance
5. Attempt to start the instance

Add function need_make_drive to check the instance config_drive
setting is None, while the config_drive is needed. And remove the
config setting in the disk info when nova compute attempts to start
an instance.

Fixes bug: 1356534

Change-Id: Ia1750bfa9ec096069ed08e7ac96b25a51e42a7b1

With the reference implementation, there exists a problem when using
'nova-interface-attach' using 'net-id' parameter. The neutron port
created for this operation does not inherit the instance's security-groups,
but instead uses just the 'default' security-group.

The proposed fix is to use the instance's security-groups when allocating
port for the instance.

However, if port-security extension is present and port-security-enabled
is set to False for the network on which we are trying to attach interface,
then the code had a check to raise an error. This patch removes the code
raising that error and instead does not use the passed security-groups
when creating a port in such a network.

commit_message:
neutron port security-group improperly updated on nova interface-attach

With the reference implementation, there exists a problem when using
'nova-interface-attach' using 'net-id' parameter. The neutron port
created for this operation does not inherit the instance's security-groups,
but instead uses just the 'default' security-group.

The proposed fix is to use the instance's security-groups when allocating
port for the instance.

However, if port-security extension is present and port-security-enabled
is set to False for the network on which we are trying to attach interface,
then the code had a check to raise an error. This patch removes the code
raising that error and instead does not use the passed security-groups
when creating a port in such a network.

Change-Id: I59d9a9f3caa5efb49c005bda104eadaf63bc3c8b
Closes-Bug: #1406431
Co-Authored-By: Praveen Yalagandula <ypraveen@avinetworks.com>

commit_message:
fix 'Ignoring EndpointNotFound' error in init host

Add init=True in _delete_instance when init_host,
and raise exception when EndpointNotFound exists.
It will set vm's status to error and make user can
re-issue a delete.

Change-Id: I67eccc2b60fbe6b9b20cd2d090ba94467efc3d76
Closes-bug: #1408865

commit_message:
Fix for live migration rollback when using shared storage

If compute nodes use shared-storage no network cleanup happens
on destionation node. So cleanup flag is set to True for every type
of live-migration. Also changed logic for destroy disks.

Closes-bug: #1284719

Change-Id: I205e2d31ec0b29cee76fa2ba72b3e48a7b788b02

commit_message:
Detect a last man standing for rabbit OCF agent

W/o this patch, the race condition is possible
when there is no running rabbit nodes/resource
master. The rabbit nodes will start/stop in an
endless loop as a result introducing full downtime
for AMQP cluster and cloud control plane.

The solution is:
* On post-start/post-promote notify, do nothing, if
  either of the following is a true:
  - there is no rabbit resources running or no master
  - the list of rabbit resources being started/promoted
    reported empty
* For such cases, do not report resource failure and delegate
  recovery, if needed, to the "running out of the cluster"
  monitor's logic.
* Additionally, report about a last man standing when
  there is no running rabbit resources around.

Closes-bug: #1491306

Change-Id: If1c62fac26b63410636413c49fce55c35e53dc5f
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

revisions:
[{'number': 12, 'created': '2015-09-04 11:16:42.000000000', 'files': ['files/fuel-ha-utils/ocf/rabbitmq'], 'message': 'Make RabbitMQ OCF script tolerate rabbitmqctl timeouts

The change makes OCF script ignore small number of timeouts of rabbitmqctl
for 'heavy' operations: list_channels, get_alarms and list_queues.
Number of tolerated timeouts in a row is configured through a new variable
'max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts'. By default it is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl
timeouts are not tolerated at all.

Bug #1487517 is fixed by extracting declaration of local variables
'rc_alarms' and 'rc_queues' from assignment operations.


Text for Operations Guide:

If on node where RabbitMQ is deployed
other processes consume significant part of CPU, RabbitMQ starts
responding slow to queries by 'rabbitmqctl' utility. The utility is
used by RabbitMQ's OCF script to monitor state of the RabbitMQ.
When utility fails to return in pre-defined timeout, OCF script
considers RabbitMQ to be down and restarts it, which might lead to
a limited (several minutes) OpenStack downtime. Such restarts
are undesirable as they cause downtime without benefit. To
mitigate the issue, the OCF script might be told to tolerate
certain amount of rabbitmqctl timeouts in a row using the following
command:
  crm_resource --resource p_rabbitmq-server --set-parameter \
      max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts --parameter-value N

Here N should be replaced with the number of timeouts. For instance,
if it is set to 3, the OCF script will tolerate two rabbitmqctl
timeouts in a row, but fail if the third one occurs.

By default the parameter is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl timeout is not
tolerated at all. The downside of increasing the parameter is that
if a real issue occurs which causes rabbitmqctl timeout, OCF script
will detect that only after N monitor runs and so the restart, which
might fix the issue, will be delayed.

To understand that RabbitMQ's restart was caused by rabbitmqctl timeout
you should examine lrmd.log of the corresponding controller on Fuel
master node in /var/log/docker-logs/remote/ directory. Here lines like
"the invoked command exited 137: /usr/sbin/rabbitmqctl list_channels ..."

indicate rabbitmqctl timeout. The next line will explain if it
caused restart or not. For example:
"rabbitmqctl timed out 2 of max. 3 time(s) in a row. Doing nothing for now."

DocImpact: user-guide, operations-guide

Closes-Bug: #1479815
Closes-Bug: #1487517
Change-Id: I9dec06fc08dbeefbc67249b9e9633c8aab5e09ca
'}]
commit_message:
Make RabbitMQ OCF script tolerate rabbitmqctl timeouts

The change makes OCF script ignore small number of timeouts of rabbitmqctl
for 'heavy' operations: list_channels, get_alarms and list_queues.
Number of tolerated timeouts in a row is configured through a new variable
'max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts'. By default it is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl
timeouts are not tolerated at all.

Bug #1487517 is fixed by extracting declaration of local variables
'rc_alarms' and 'rc_queues' from assignment operations.


Text for Operations Guide:

If on node where RabbitMQ is deployed
other processes consume significant part of CPU, RabbitMQ starts
responding slow to queries by 'rabbitmqctl' utility. The utility is
used by RabbitMQ's OCF script to monitor state of the RabbitMQ.
When utility fails to return in pre-defined timeout, OCF script
considers RabbitMQ to be down and restarts it, which might lead to
a limited (several minutes) OpenStack downtime. Such restarts
are undesirable as they cause downtime without benefit. To
mitigate the issue, the OCF script might be told to tolerate
certain amount of rabbitmqctl timeouts in a row using the following
command:
  crm_resource --resource p_rabbitmq-server --set-parameter \
      max_rabbitmqctl_timeouts --parameter-value N

Here N should be replaced with the number of timeouts. For instance,
if it is set to 3, the OCF script will tolerate two rabbitmqctl
timeouts in a row, but fail if the third one occurs.

By default the parameter is set to 1, i.e. rabbitmqctl timeout is not
tolerated at all. The downside of increasing the parameter is that
if a real issue occurs which causes rabbitmqctl timeout, OCF script
will detect that only after N monitor runs and so the restart, which
might fix the issue, will be delayed.

To understand that RabbitMQ's restart was caused by rabbitmqctl timeout
you should examine lrmd.log of the corresponding controller on Fuel
master node in /var/log/docker-logs/remote/ directory. Here lines like
"the invoked command exited 137: /usr/sbin/rabbitmqctl list_channels ..."

indicate rabbitmqctl timeout. The next line will explain if it
caused restart or not. For example:
"rabbitmqctl timed out 2 of max. 3 time(s) in a row. Doing nothing for now."

DocImpact: user-guide, operations-guide

Closes-Bug: #1479815
Closes-Bug: #1487517
Change-Id: I9dec06fc08dbeefbc67249b9e9633c8aab5e09ca

commit_message:
Add PciNumaInfoWeigher

On some hosts numa node info is not reported for pci devices.
This weigher will allow Nova to prioritize hosts that properly
report numa node info during scheduling. If a VM doesn't request
PCI devices all host will have same weight.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint input-output-based-numa-scheduling

Change-Id: Ibaafc5bed8663273cb47d2dc1b3b96caf1b8e2aa

commit_message:
rbd: use rbd snapshots and cloning for ephemeral disk snapshots

When rbd is used for ephemeral disks and image storage, we can avoid
local disk by doing the snapshot with ceph, and sending the location
of it to glance.

At this point glance is effectively the owner of the snapshot, and
nova cannot delete the original disk, so a corresponding change to
glance is needed to handle this cleanup later, when the snapshot is
deleted.

To accomplish this, create an rbd clone and store the clone's location
in glance, and when nova deletes an rbd disk with snapshots, rename
the disk to include a marker that glance looks for to know they can be
deleted when glance deletes the snapshots.

This requires changing the typical permissions for the glance ceph
user to allow writing to the pool where vm images are stored.

DocImpact: glance will need write access to rbd to delete snapshots
Change-Id: Idefa95f126f2922acf008038e2ac7430b1d26a33
Implements: blueprint implement-rbd-snapshots-instead-of-qemu-snapshots
Closes-Bug: 1346525

commit_message:
Integrate OSprofiler and Nova

*) Add osprofiler wsgi middleware
This middleware is used for 2 things:
1) It checks that person who want to trace is trusted and knows
secret HMAC key.
2) It start tracing in case of proper trace headers
and add first wsgi trace point, with info about HTTP request

*) Add initialization of osprofiler at start of serivce
Set's olso.messaging notifer instance (to send notifications to Ceilometer)

*) Fix fake notifier

Based on: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/105096/

Co-Authored-By: Boris Pavlovic <boris@pavlovic.me>

Change-Id: I23b6e4f466c81bc8ebd1a85ceb3689fffa379674
Signed-off-by: Munoz, Obed N <obed.n.munoz@intel.com>

commit_message:
Revert "turn multi host true for nova network by default"

This reverts commit 2e1a91c50b73ca7f46871d3a906ade93bbcac6a7

It looks like this introduced race bug 1491949 in the
gate-tempest-dsvm-large-ops job causing rpc timeouts when
deallocating network information for an instance,
specifically around the dnsmasq callback to release the
fixed IP that the instance was using which triggers the
disassociation between the fixed IP and the instance in the
nova database.

Change-Id: I163cdeea75e92485f241647c69aea0d7456c3258
Closes-Bug: #1491949

commit_message:
Disable v3 API by default

Since v3 is still unstable and has experimental status it's
better to disable it by default for security reasons. This
commit does it by setting 'enable_v3_api=False'.

Also all required documentation was added to related sections.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I412d0645d667400333532123008a24966aa23880

commit_message:
Fix keystone client usage in barbican client

In magnum.common.clients, barbican client uses
`keystone()._client` directly, but `keystone().client`
is better. Because, keystone()._client is None is it
is not loaded.

This fixes it.

Closes-Bug: #1491257
Change-Id: I3771ebef9c2a1d3756ea4ed2f964751d1c2da43f

commit_message:
Allow to use autodetection of volume device path

API contract says, device is optional. We should allow the
device property to be nullable
http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2.1.html#attachVolume

Note that in python nova client "auto" is turned into None for the
device before the call is made to Nova API.

Closes-Bug: #1491325
Change-Id: Ibfd83b6abdfeec328019246a372363cada53869e

commit_message:
Introduce unit test for genconfig

We don't have unit test for genconfig, so sometimes this feature
is broken because of missing options or moving options.
This patch adds checking test for config parameters.

Change-Id: I67a44ef02704f66740a6bda2b6502b6b1636a08b
Closes-Bug: #1490825

[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-08-24 22:48:18.000000000', 'files': ['tox.ini'], 'message': 'Disable pep8 check E127

Let's say you have some code like this:

class TestStuff(unittest.TestCase):
    def test_a_thing(self):
        # [setup code goes here]
        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
             mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
             mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

pep8 will complain about this with a pair of messages like this: "E127
continuation line over-indented for visual indent", plus some line
numbers. It's complaining about the indentations of the second and
third lines in the 'with' clause.

Okay, so it's over-indented. Let's indent it less.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
           mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
           mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Now it's uglier, and pep8 still says it's over-indented. Keep going:

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
          mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
          mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Nope.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
         mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
         mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Still no.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
        mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
        mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Still no. Different error this time, though.

Okay, let's try adding some spaces to see if that'll make it less...
over-indented. *sigh*

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
              mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
              mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Nope. You sick of this yet? I sure am.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
               mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
               mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

ARGH

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
                mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
                mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Three spaces works! Hallelujah! How about four?

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
                 mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
                 mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

BAHAHA no.

Got it? When pep8 says that a continuation line is over-indented, you
need to add exactly three spaces. Three shall be the number thou shalt
count, and the number of the counting shall be three. Four shalt thou
not count, neither count thou two, excepting that thou then proceed to
three. Five is right out.

This commit blacklists E127 so nobody else has to waste time on this
garbage.

Change-Id: Ifbcf3c2ee04d9636135ae6dcd606d595acb4b815
'}]
commit_message:
Disable pep8 check E127

Let's say you have some code like this:

class TestStuff(unittest.TestCase):
    def test_a_thing(self):
        # [setup code goes here]
        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
             mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
             mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

pep8 will complain about this with a pair of messages like this: "E127
continuation line over-indented for visual indent", plus some line
numbers. It's complaining about the indentations of the second and
third lines in the 'with' clause.

Okay, so it's over-indented. Let's indent it less.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
           mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
           mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Now it's uglier, and pep8 still says it's over-indented. Keep going:

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
          mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
          mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Nope.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
         mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
         mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Still no.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
        mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
        mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Still no. Different error this time, though.

Okay, let's try adding some spaces to see if that'll make it less...
over-indented. *sigh*

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
              mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
              mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Nope. You sick of this yet? I sure am.

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
               mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
               mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

ARGH

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
                mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
                mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

Three spaces works! Hallelujah! How about four?

        with mock.patch("swift.obj.auditor.os.wait", fake_os_wait), \
                 mock.patch.object(my_auditor, 'fork_child', fake_fork_child), \
                 mock.patch.object(my_auditor, '_sleep', lambda *a: None):
            my_auditor.run_once()

BAHAHA no.

Got it? When pep8 says that a continuation line is over-indented, you
need to add exactly three spaces. Three shall be the number thou shalt
count, and the number of the counting shall be three. Four shalt thou
not count, neither count thou two, excepting that thou then proceed to
three. Five is right out.

This commit blacklists E127 so nobody else has to waste time on this
garbage.

commit_message:
Add claim for evacuate operations

Nova only set host and node when it wants to evacuate
an instance. Unlink other operations such as unshelve or
create, there is no claim means sometimes the host might
have enough resource will still do the evacuate operations.
This patch adds check for resources when doing evacuate.

Change-Id: Ia7167d8c5f49820907a292663f5c43c852a8e824
Partial-Bug: #1289064

commit_message:
Integrated with PyKMIP Pie API

The PyKMIP Pie API provides a simpler interface for communicating with
KMIP devices. The interface is simplified to allow KMIP integrators to
quickly be able to communicate with a KMIP device. It does not provide
all of the KMIP optional parameters, but those features are not
required for integration with KMIP in the KMIP secret store.

Depends-On: I568a28288068c6016dc67244d979d3619874a425
Change-Id: Ie6f71752eb4d7c7f01942b3881db7a4aa424cb49

commit_message:
Update the minimum glanceclient version

A bug is present in glanceclient versions 0.16.1 and 0.17.0 which means
that https connections can not be established between nova and glance,
causing API requests to fail.

Bump the minimum supported version to prevent users hitting this issue.

Conflicts:
	global-requirements.txt

Change-Id: Id10e46166b90e67b013512476fb546f463316a1e
Related-bug: 1442664
(cherry picked from commit e586a0a72774578e2d1d8b399538eb39c4b88492)

commit_message:
Updating stable/juno glance_store cap

glance_store 0.3.0 was recently released and the team is also moving to
maintaining stable branches for this library. Therefore, this patch
bumps the stable version for glance_store to <0.4.0 so that it pulls in
0.3.0 and all its future patches releases.

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-01-13 10:06:00.000000000', 'files': ['global-requirements.txt'], 'message': 'Add sphinx_rtd_theme to enhance doc gate jobs

When it gets to submitting & reviewing patches for the project documentation,
it is very convenient to surf through the docs generated by Sphinx in a special
Gate job. The problem is that Sphinx uses in gates a theme which is different
from that used on ReadTheDocs. So the docs generated in gates look differently
from the docs that we have on ReadTheDocs, while the desired behaviour is to
have the same Sphinx theme both on ReadTheDocs and in gates.

There is a snippet that enables this theme for Sphinx locally (and so in gates):
http://paste.openstack.org/show/156901/

It is going to be used, for example, here:
https://review.openstack.org/120018

This code uses the sphinx_rtd_theme python package, so we need to include it
into global requirements.

Change-Id: I61dad599279b0dd94a70adcfd415f5a97701a5c4
'}]
commit_message:
Add sphinx_rtd_theme to enhance doc gate jobs

When it gets to submitting & reviewing patches for the project documentation,
it is very convenient to surf through the docs generated by Sphinx in a special
Gate job. The problem is that Sphinx uses in gates a theme which is different
from that used on ReadTheDocs. So the docs generated in gates look differently
from the docs that we have on ReadTheDocs, while the desired behaviour is to
have the same Sphinx theme both on ReadTheDocs and in gates.

There is a snippet that enables this theme for Sphinx locally (and so in gates):
http://paste.openstack.org/show/156901/

It is going to be used, for example, here:
https://review.openstack.org/120018

This code uses the sphinx_rtd_theme python package, so we need to include it
into global requirements.

Change-Id: I61dad599279b0dd94a70adcfd415f5a97701a5c4

commit_message:
Use diff --exit-code instead of --quiet

git diff --quiet has been reported to not return the expected exit
status in some circumstances (see
https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1264422). This change matches
what devstack does, and uses --exit-code instead of --quiet.

This has also been submitted to openstack-dev/pbr
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/146958/).

Change-Id: I149b3b5faa793eb2b6b8e0ae636f5e93a2f1fb71
Related-Bug: #1410434

commit_message:
Update global requirements to reflect requirements of AMQP1 driver

oslo.messaging AMQP1 driver has its own requirements, so it does
make sense to reflect them in global requirements

Here's a list of missing requirements:
- Requirement pyngus>=1.0.0,<2.0.0 not in openstack/requirements
- Requirement python-qpid-proton>=0.7,<0.8 not in openstack/requirements

Requirements list can be generated using project-config
check-requirements tool (see references below).

Change-Id: Ie6768b54a5638b07af2a93d68cc2857d6a49ed76
Needed-By: I893f9a1c259157bc6e6829fe34067ede365c15b7 (project-config)

commit_message:
Remove last vestige of glanceclient being different

There is an ongoing transition across OpenStack from endpoint_type
to interface. New glanceclient uses the new form, so we support both
and can remove the copy/pasta in the glance_client constructor.

Change-Id: I63f70a0102eb7d7982eacf28ff14642550942911

subject: Fix exception lists in functional tests
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 2, 'name': 'Monty Taylor', 'email': 'mordred@inaugust.com', 'username': 'mordred'}, {'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 6133, 'name': 'yolanda.robla', 'email': 'yroblamo@redhat.com', 'username': 'yolanda.robla'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-09-02 23:49:56.000000000', 'files': ['shade/tests/functional/test_floating_ip.py', 'shade/tests/functional/test_port.py', 'shade/tests/functional/test_flavor.py', 'shade/tests/functional/test_endpoints.py', 'shade/tests/functional/test_services.py'], 'message': 'Fix exception lists in functional tests

There is a pattern in our functional tests where exceptions are
aggregated within a list and then joined within a single string.
However, the join expects them as strings, not as exception objects.
When this code is hit, it causes an exception:

TypeError: sequence item 0: expected string, OpenStackCloudException found

This change converts those exception objects to strings.

Change-Id: I0a041a61537b79c73615e5136492141da0926fee

commit_message:
Fix exception lists in functional tests

There is a pattern in our functional tests where exceptions are
aggregated within a list and then joined within a single string.
However, the join expects them as strings, not as exception objects.
When this code is hit, it causes an exception:

TypeError: sequence item 0: expected string, OpenStackCloudException found

This change converts those exception objects to strings.

Change-Id: I0a041a61537b79c73615e5136492141da0926fee

commit_message:
Replace deprecated SortedDict with OrderedDict

Class django.utils.datastructures.SortedDict is deprecated since
Django 1.7 (removed in Django 1.9) and should be replaced with
collections.OrderedDict.

Closes-Bug: #1492270

Change-Id: Ib1c0c898c716803bf9c39827d588351c332993db

commit_message:
libvirt: add more logging and result checking around attachDeviceFlags

This is really grasping at straws but commit ef9dedb2f which introduced
this code in the guest module changed passing flags from a positional
argument to a kwarg and we're wondering if that is somehow messing up
how PyArg_ParseTuple is handling this - like maybe the underlying
libvirt just never gets called.

Also adds return code checking on attachDeviceFlags since if it's not
failing and raising libvirtError, we want to make sure it's at least
returning 0, and not something unexpected like None.

Log the flags while we're at it.

Related-Bug: #1492026

Change-Id: I04688f50b70dfbe19f2fcac8c9bc12c0940ef4fd

commit_message:
turn multi host true for nova network by default

With multi host set to true devstack's dnsmasq server no longer
listens on the network to other systems. In the gate we can see we're
getting a ton of spurious dhcp requests from other systems on the
network, and it's better that we never even see it.

Change-Id: Ie600de91e4a7da734eae722e78101c2401a7b1f5

commit_message:
Remove Local flow installation From the L2 Agent to L3 Controller

Move the flow installation for translating the tunnel id
into the nicira extension marking, from the local l2 agent into the
L3 application using OpenFlow RYU framework.

This patch is dependent on the commit of the following patch in RYU
https://github.com/osrg/ryu/commit/815dc505b750ed7ea61d01ee7eaf767de6b377cc
Note: require upgrade of the Ryu lib to the latest stable to solve the
bug but version check was added to support older ryu version on the
stable branch

Closes-Bug: #1480786
Change-Id: I909e1adce889685c17aba528ace1ebb7d0ed52a2
(cherry picked from commit 4183e65ce360800ec915e65531c0e28fc3f2e152)

commit_message:
[gates] Convert Rally to the new Devstack plugin model

Switch Rally integration with Devstack to the new plugin model [1].
This allows to install Rally by one line in localrc, without
copying any files by hand. It also may make setting CI jobs easier.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/devstack/plugins.html

* Remove Sahara pluging from Rally gate job

Sahara was removed from default services that run DevStack in gates
We need to remove these scenarios from rally.yaml and add separate job
for Sahara

Depends-on: I845178bd51f2623fa56bb97f8bd5f2e4e7553613
Change-Id: Ia4e211dbf50d13068502c27c26cf5e3199542ce7

commit_message:
Role * supported for deployment tasks

of tasks names in role field.
Duplication of test 'test_check_group_type_deployment_task' removed.

that v2.0 on v2.1 and v2.0 on legacy v2.0 code pass all the Tempest
API tests.

commit_message:
Implement /usr/bin/env as the shebang in all bash scripts

In order to be more consistent, and also account for different
environments and platforms, this patch implements the use of
environment.

Closes-Bug: #1485557
Change-Id: I93e6a47fd6be816620682eddb2880e38f11bf675
(cherry picked from commit d1f410d08a5369c1a25bbd15da318b247003514a)
